04141nam a22005535i 9780822392149DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223921497 a10.1515/97808223921492doi  a(DE-B1597)552010  a(OCoLC)1136474391  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aCOM0790002bisacsh04a306.462221 aBalsamo, Anne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDesigning Culture :bThe Technological Imagination at Work /cAnne Balsamo. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (307 p.) :b33 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContents of designingculture.net -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction Taking Culture Seriously in The Age of Innovation -- tOne Gendering the Technological Imagination -- tTwo The Performance of Innovation -- tThree Public Interactives and the Design of Technological Literacies -- tFour Designing Learning -- tConclusion The Work of a Book in a Digital Age -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe renowned cultural theorist and media designer Anne Balsamo maintains that technology and culture are inseparable; those who engage in technological innovation are designing the cultures of the future. Designing Culture is a call for taking culture seriously in the design and development of innovative technologies. Balsamo contends that the wellspring of technological innovation is the technological imagination, a quality of mind that enables people to think with technology, to transform what is known into what is possible. She describes the technological imagination at work in several multimedia collaborations in which she was involved as a designer or developer. One of these entailed the creation of an interactive documentary for the NGO Forum held in conjunction with the UN World Conference on Women in Beijing in 1995. (That documentary is included as a DVD in Designing Culture.) Balsamo also recounts the development of the interactive museum exhibit XFR: Experiments in the Future of Reading, created by the group RED (Research in Experimental Documents) at Xerox PARC. She speculates on what it would mean to cultivate imaginations as ingenious in creating new democratic cultural possibilities as they are in creating new kinds of technologies and digital media. Designing Culture is a manifesto for transforming educational programs and developing learning strategies adequate to the task of inspiring culturally attuned technological imaginations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCivilization, Modern. 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.). 0aTechnological innovationsxSocial aspects. 0aTechnological literacy. 7aCOMPUTERS / Social Aspects / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822392149zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822392149423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822392149/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles